'''Herbert "Herbie" Coleridge''' (7 October 1830 – 23 April 1861) was a [[England|British]] [[philologist]], technically the first editor of what ultimately became the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]''. He was a grandson of the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.

==Biography==
He was the son of [[Sara Coleridge|Sara]] and [[Henry Nelson Coleridge]]. He earned a [[British undergraduate degree classification#First-class honours|double first]] in [[Classics]] and [[mathematics]] at [[Balliol College]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]. After graduation, he became a [[barrister]], but, living off a small [[Life annuity|annuity]], devoted most of his time and energy to linguistics studies. At age 27, as a member of the [[Philological Society]], he formed a committee with [[Richard Chenevix Trench]] and [[Frederick James Furnivall|Frederick Furnivall]] to identify and research words unlisted and undefined in English dictionaries of the period. The efforts of this committee eventually led to the development of the ''Oxford English Dictionary''. A dedicated editor, he died of [[tuberculosis]] at age 30 after completing some fundamental work for the project.

== Works ==
* ''A Glossarial Index to the Printed English Literature of the Thirteenth Century''. London: Trubner & Co., 1859. 
* ''A Dictionary of the First, or Oldest Words in the English Language: from the Semi Saxon Period of A.D. 1250 to 1300. Consisting of An Alphabetical Inventory of Every Word Found in the Printed English Literature of the 13TH Century''. London: John Camden Hotten, 1863.

