'''''Modern Indian language''''' ('''MIL''') is a term used in India to denote several Indian languages used in modern times, with or without official status. Though most Modern Indian languages are also mentioned in [[Eighth Schedule to the Constitution of India]], it is not necessary that all languages listed in either of them is listed in other one.
==Languages== Modern Indian languages are listed below.<ref>http://cbse.nic.in/curric~1/mil02.pdf</ref> * Assamese * Bengali * Bhutia * Gujarati * Kashmiri * Kannada * Lepcha * Limboo * Malayalam * Manipuri * Marathi * Mizo * Oriya * Punjabi * Sanskrit * Sindhi * Tamil * Telugu * Urdu
==Application== Most education boards in India teach at least one of the MILs in schools. UPSC requires candidates to be well versed in at least one MIL.{{cn|date=January 2018}}
==See also== * [[Less Commonly Taught Languages]]
